      "comments": [
        {
          "author_name": "Valerie Tsarenko 🇺🇦",
          "author_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/valerietsarenko",
          "text": "100%. Early user access to a product quickly shifts development from hypotheses to real-world application. It provides live feedback, highlights actual usage scenarios, and helps teams make more accurate product decisions from the very beginning.",
          "reactions": 1,
          "replies_count": 0
        },
        {
          "author_name": "Olga Minko",
          "author_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/olivia-mltn",
          "text": "A good test for any early product: can someone try it without you being there? If not, you're probably still building infrastructure, not a product.",
          "reactions": 1,
          "replies_count": 0
        },
        {
          "author_name": "Ali F.",
          "author_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/ali-f-2b4540227",
          "text": "This is so true. If someone outside your environment can't use it, it's not a product yet it's just a demo. Distribution and usability should start way earlier than most founders think.",
          "reactions": 1,
          "replies_count": 0
        }
      ]
    },
